\begin_layout Subsection
General Construction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SM is based on Quantum Field Theory (QFT).
 Here, elementary particles are considered as excitation modes of associated
 quantized fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 Dynamics are described via Lagrangian density functions.
 Starting with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Lagrangian density for fermions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L} & =\bar{\Psi}\left(i\slashed\partial-m\right)\Psi,\qquad\slashed\partial=\gamma_{\mu}\frac{\partial}{\partial x^{\mu}},\qquad\bar{\Psi}=\Psi^{\dagger}\gamma_{0},
\end{align}

\end_inset

one can obtain the equation of motion (for fermions: the Dirac equation)
 the by using the Euler-Lagrangian equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0=\frac{\partial}{\partial x_{\mu}}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial\left(\partial\bar{\Psi}/\partial x_{\mu}\right)}\right)-\frac{\partial}{\partial\bar{\Psi}}\mathcal{L}=\left(i\slashed\partial-m\right)\Psi.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interactions can be introduced by requiring that the Lagrangian density
 is invariant under a local gauge transformation of the field 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the electromagnetic interactions is obtained by postulating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\Psi & \rightarrow\Psi^{\prime}=\Psi\cdot e^{-iq\alpha(x)}
\end{align}

\end_inset

with the free chosen local phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha(x)$
\end_inset

 and the EM charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.
 This transforms the Lagrangian density to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Rightarrow\mathcal{L}\rightarrow\mathcal{L}^{\prime}=\bar{\Psi}(i\slashed\partial+q\slashed\partial\alpha(x)-m)\Psi.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The requirement for invariance of the Lagrangian density 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}\left(\Psi^{\prime}\right)=\mathcal{L}\left(\Psi\right)$
\end_inset

 under such transformation can be solved by adding the additional photon
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\mu}$
\end_inset

.
 It transforms under local gauge transformation to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{\mu}\rightarrow A_{\mu}^{\prime}=A_{\mu}-\partial_{\mu}\alpha(x).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Rightarrow\mathcal{L}=\underbrace{-\frac{1}{4}F_{\mu\nu}F^{\mu\nu}}_{\mathrm{photon\, propagator}}+\underbrace{\bar{\Psi}\left(i\slashed\partial-m\right)\Psi}_{\mathrm{fermion\, propagator}}-\underbrace{q\bar{\Psi}\gamma_{\mu}\Psi A^{\mu}}_{\mathrm{interaction}},\qquad F_{\mu\nu}=\partial_{\mu}A_{\nu}-\partial_{\nu}A_{\mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where additionally the already gauge invariant photon propagator has as
 been added.
 This construction procedure predicts that the photon is massless.
 Extending the Lagrangian density with a mass term proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $\propto m_{\gamma}^{2}A_{\mu}A^{\mu}$
\end_inset

 violates the invariance.
 Furthermore, at the interactions vertex, the conservation of angular momentum
 states that the photon is a boson with spin 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, the Lagrangian density of the electromagnetic interactions
 is determined by requiring local gauge invariance.
 Weak and strong interactions are as well connected to a certain gauge group
 transformation.
 However, experiments 
