\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{SU(3)}$
\end_inset

 gauge charge is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

color
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 QCD demonstrates new effects through its non-abelian gauge group.
 Experiments have shown that no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 quarks could be observed so far.
 This effect can be explained through a modified potential between quarks
 which leads to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

confinement
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Bounded states of quarks appear in color singulets of mesons (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}\bar{\mathrm{q}}$
\end_inset

) or baryons (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{qqq}$
\end_inset

).
 Moreover, it is possible to produce additional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{q}\bar{\mathrm{q}}$
\end_inset

 pairs from the vacuum if the potential exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot m_{\mathrm{q}}$
\end_inset

.
 This process of grouping and pair production is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hadronization
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and can not be calculated perturbatively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, QCD scattering processes can be calculated in a perturbative way
 through the behavior of the running coupling constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\alpha_{s}(q^{2})=\frac{\alpha_{s}(\mu_{R}^{2})}{1+\left(\alpha_{s}(\mu_{R}^{2})\cdot\frac{33-2\cdot n_{f}}{12\pi}\right)\cdot\ln\left(\frac{\left|q^{2}\right|}{\mu_{R}^{2}}\right)}
\end{equation}

