\begin_layout Subsection
Anomalous Couplings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of new particles or interactions to the top quark electroweak
 couplings can be parametrized by using the Operator Product Expansion (OPE).
 New products of operators may arise from new interactions at a higher energy
 scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Those can be develop around their spatial separation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "peskin"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{O}_{1}(x)\mathcal{O}_{2}(0)\rightarrow\sum_{j}C_{12}^{j}(x)\mathcal{O}_{j}(0)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This can be understood as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}\rightarrow\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{SM}}+\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{eff}}=\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{SM}}+\sum_{j}\left(\frac{v}{\Lambda}\right)^{j}\mathcal{O}_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
checkthis{need ref!!}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 denotes the vacuum expectation value of the Higgs potential.
 In the case of the top quark, the SM Lagrangian density 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{Wtb}}^{\mathrm{SM}}=-\frac{g}{\sqrt{2}}\bar{\mathrm{b}}\gamma^{\mu}\mbox{\mathrm{V_{tb}}}\mbox{\mathrm{P_{L}}}\mathrm{t}\mathrm{W_{\mu}^{-}}+\mathrm{h.c.}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be extended in an effective coupling scenario 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Wtb-top-pair"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{Wtb}}^{\mathrm{eff}}= & -\frac{g}{\sqrt{2}}\bar{\mathrm{b}}\gamma^{\mu}\left(\mathrm{V_{L}}\mathrm{P_{L}}+\mathrm{V_{R}}\mathrm{P_{R}}\right)\mathrm{t}\mathrm{W}_{\mu}^{-} & \mathrm{(vector\, couplings)}\\
 & -\frac{g}{\sqrt{2}}\bar{\mathrm{b}}\frac{i\sigma^{\mu\nu}q_{\nu}}{m_{W}}\left(\mathrm{g_{L}P_{L}+g_{R}P_{R}}\right)\mathrm{t}\mathrm{W}_{\mu}^{-}+\mbox{\mathrm{h.c.}} & \mathrm{\left(tensor\, couplings\right)}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

The scale dependence 
\begin_inset Formula ${\textstyle \frac{v}{\Lambda}}$
\end_inset

 has been absorbed into the new coupling strength parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V_{R},\, g_{L}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{g_{R}}$
\end_inset

.
 The SM is obtained by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V_{L}=V_{tb}}\approx1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V_{R}=g_{L}=g_{R}=0}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V_{R}}$
\end_inset

 introduces a new right-handed vector anomalous coupling and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{g_{L},\, g_{R}}$
\end_inset

 new tensor left-, right-handed anomalous couplings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
W Boson Helicity Fractions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One way of probing the presence of anomalous couplings is by analyzing the
 W boson helicity fractions.
 The W boson spin is quantized along its momentum in the top quark rest
 frame.
 The angle between the lepton in the W boson rest frame and the quantized
 spin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\theta^{\star}$
\end_inset

, then follows the distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\mathrm{d}\Gamma}{\Gamma\cdot\mathrm{d}\cos\theta^{\star}}= & \frac{3}{8}\left(1+\cos\theta^{\star}\right)^{2}\cdot\mathrm{F}_{+}+\frac{3}{8}\left(1-\cos\theta^{\star}\right)^{2}\cdot\mathrm{F}_{-}\\
 & +\frac{3}{4}\sin^{2}\theta^{\star}\cdot\mathrm{F}_{0}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
